This is a gorgeous Tasmanian waterfall, one of many, this one on the Groom River, and fed by a hand-built 19th century weir upstream and built by Chinese miners searching for tin in this mineral-rich area.  Tin was used to make oil lamps, lanterns, pots and pans and was much sought-after at the time. Meandering through eucalypts and temperate rainforest myrtle trees and tall ferns, I ended up here, in paradise, all alone. It kinda reminds me of Jurassic Park, but I cannot report seeing any dinosaurs (CAN YOU IMAGINE!?!?) 😆
.
P.S. I take you here on my Tasmania East Coast photo tour.....taking bookings now for 26 March to 1 April 2023...........message me!

Meandering around the cute narrow, solid timber boardwalks around Cradle Mountain is an exceptional experience. To me, the boardwalks are such an integral part of the walks as they look so inviting, all zig zagging between the trees, sturdy and safe. Of course, they protect the surrounding environment by managing where you walk, and you are left with untouched moss covered trees; inhaling fertile, leafy, earthy, forest scents, and every shade of green imaginable is a magical sight: green, olive, jade, emerald, evergreen, khaki, avocado, lime, sage……the list goes on and on. The Cradle Mountain forest experience is something I’d love to share with you in 2023, make sure you are subscribed to my email newsletters (go to me website or message me to send you a link) to hear of my upcoming photo tour experience in a different part of Tasmania. 🌿
.
For those of you who are photographers, I have never quite been able to capture the forest/rainforest greens as I wanted, until this trip. I experimented with using a CPL filter to cut some of the light glare, but wasn’t happy. I ended up shooting a full 3 stops under most times, and felt that this gave me the best results. I also found that using a tripod definitely enhanced my images and allowed me to capture the shots I wanted. I ditched my wide angle lens too, and went for a 24-70 which allowed me to shrink down the sometimes busy composition of so, so much to look at. Would love to know your thoughts! What works for you with forest greens?

You may know that I LOVE ME A JETTY but I was far, far away from the ocean at Cradle Mountain. Luckily some clever park ranger designer architect person designed so many gorgeous boardwalks, and from this one leading into Dove Lake, I found my jetty. Well, kinda. Pretty cool to see the ‘cradle’ that Cradle Mountain is  named after too, a few minutes later the cloud was pretty much covering it all again. Alpine areas are renowned for crazy and swift changing weather conditions, and Cradle is no exception! 💨🌨⛅️

Is it honestly still called ‘Secret Falls’ if it isn’t a secret? I dunno, but I do remember the very first time I tried to find this waterfall years ago, hidden away below the track to another waterfall, and the only way I was able to find it was because I heard voices below and I knew there was a little goat track around somewhere. This time it was easier to find, however it was much wetter than the last time….and way more slippery and muddy after a lot of rain…..but it looked gorgeous! Tip: if you want to keep it a secret, don’t make any noise! 🌿🌿

On a photography road trip, of COURSE you have to stop for snow! It’s a must!. The snow was so wet, the speckles landed all over my lens and really made it challenging, but I didn’t care. It was so pretty. You never know what you’re going to get in Tassie, weather-wise, every season is amazing, and you might see them all in the same day. Come with me next year when I take you to some beautiful parts of Tasmania to enjoy the scenery and just….take photos. Lots of them. I’m on hand to guide you and help you improve your compositions, and to show you some new tips and tricks as well. Message me for info, or check my website for deets. 🌿

Minimalism at its best………the Astoria-Megler Bridge, this time from the Washington side. There is something about this bridge that really captured my attention. Made to withstand incredibly strong wind and river current conditions, it’s just a beautiful subject to photograph, from any angle. Once a year (in October) the bridge is open to pedestrians and wow what a long walk that would be to get across it…..almost 7 kilometres! I’m a huge fan and I can’t wait to photograph it again 😉

Rolling desert hills, basalt rock cliffs, what a beautiful surprise Yakima Canyon was on my USA road trip. I chatted with people preparing to go white water rafting down the river…with their gorgeous Labrador dog! And campers in the area who love to hike there. It’s also popular for bird watching, fly fishing, and photography. And of course…..a little suspension bridge or two! Next time maybe I’ll even have time to do some hikes there. But on this trip, I just enjoyed the 32km stretch of gorgeous nature on my last morning in Washington USA. It was like an oasis in the middle of nowhere! 🌿

I know. I’m a bit weird. But don’t you see the beauty too? The challenge for me was to create an image with SOME negative space around the sticks because there were just so many of them in the water (hashtag first world problems). 💙💙

In amongst it………..in Oregon on a road surrounded by soooo many green trees, love it! It’s not so fun when you end up behind a scary looking dude and his wife in an old pick-up truck and they think we are following them though….that’s not so fun at all. They pulled up and stared us down, and we stopped next to them and had a somewhat friendly chat, letting them know that we were just tourists off the beaten track and we weren’t trying to start anything……..or follow them…………(the USA quite frankly is a little bit daunting since everyone carries a  G U N  but whatever….). Anyway we got an ALMOST smile in the end and went on our merry way. Well it wasn’t merry, it was a little bit stressful (thank goodness for car snacks). But then there was a break in the tree canopy and I flew my drone and it was ok again. Travel. Always something happening! 😳

So on New Year’s Day 2023 I woke up early and went up to a saltwater lake half an hour away to photograph a tree, only it looked really average, some branches were no longer there and it looked a little raggedy to be honest, and the sky was bleh. So I went to my Plan B location (beach) where it was STILL bleh and windy, and I had JUST enough time to go to my Plan C location and there, I found happiness and a beautiful burnt orange cloudy sky and sweet salty air and only a few random people at the end of the boardwalk. The foamy surf reminded my of a meringue. 
This area of the beach is accessible via a boardwalk. Some time ago a clever sausage at the Council decided that what the boardwalk really needed was a thick solid white line painted down the exact middle of it, as if people couldn’t work out which side to walk on if there were others coming in an opposite direction. It has always been my habit, in Australia, to walk on the left, drive on the left, cycle on the left, rollerblade on the left, so it didn’t seem a stretch the think that boardwalks might be the same, but whatever. I found this white line to look a little bit RIDICULOUS and I’m happy to say that it has slowly worn away, almost back to just plain old weathered timber, as it should be. OH! and also, my R6 camera has now been returned to me after having all the insides replaced, and I forgot that all the settings were factory settings, and I shot all my morning photos in JPEG instead of RAW, but I have fixed that now, and tweaked everything else to my satisfaction. I feel like my rambles might be returning!! 😁

It’s interesting, being a photographer. We seem to be never truly satisfied with our work. I get hung up on technical things sometimes, like on this image, where it’s blown out on the right hand side where the sun was rising like a laser beam. After sitting on this image for a very long time (months??) I realised that I didn’t give a flying f** about that. I love the reflections, and the fact that the river water was so clear you could see the ripples of sand underneath the surface. It said ‘peace and quiet’ to me. Everyone has to do their own thing. Don’t copy others but learn from them and create your own style. It’s not like I’m a brain surgeon, saving lives. I capture images of things that interest ME, firstly always. You should do the same, regardless of ‘photography rules’ or other photographers criticising your images. 😁

Yesterday was quite the day.....despite weather warnings for major storms, rain and hail, I thought, why not go see the sunflowers, it’s only a 7+ hour round trip drive!! 😄 So we hopped into the car and as we got out to a crop near Nobby, we noticed it was 39C, and the dramatic sky was in the other direction than these sunflowers were facing….actually they are probably all droopy and sad because of 1) the heat and 2) they were ready for harvesting. Still, the butterflies, bees and birds swooping in and around made it really lovely. What did not make it lovely were the sticky flies that kept crawling into my eyes, nose and ears. I think I swallowed a few too, because why not. Anyway, it was a LONG day in the car for a couple of hours of balancing on my handy stepladder at the side of the road to get a bit of height in my images….luckily I’ve been working on my balance at the gym. I knew it would come in handy one day! If you want to know where the sunflowers are in bloom, contact the Warwick Qld Visitor Information Centre or the Southern Downs and Granite Belt Visitor Information Centre, and the lovely people there may have the intel you are seeking. Enjoy! 🌻

So if you’ve followed me for a while, you have noticed that I rarely put the exact location where I shoot, it’s often a more general location. Some locations are obvious (ie: Sydney Opera House, etc) but often its wayyyy more challenging and fun to find places yourself (I am currently on a little hunt to find a particular drone location myself and it's driving me crazy but I will get there). Don’t be insulted if I don’t share the locations, even in a DM, and I don’t expect other photographers to tell me either. I’ve noticed some Instagrammers/ influencers/ photographers who aggressively message to get an answer, and to those people I say, bugger off. A former sports figure and now a travel influencer of some sort, being paid by tourism councils, messaged me to find out a location of an image. First of all, they were not polite, they didn’t say, 'hey how are you going? I was wondering…'.all they said was ‘WHERE IS THAT’. That was it. The whole message. They were not following me, they did not like or comment on my post, just sent that message. A whole bunch of responses went through my head but in the end, I just ignored it. What happened to politeness? What happened to manners? And if a BRAND is paying you to take photos of an area, do your own freaking research. That is all. Love. 💙 Lesson: don't be a wanker.

It’s not very often I share an image from the same actual morning that I took it, but there you go. Today was beautiful! The sound of the ocean waves is like nothing else I have ever heard, it’s just amazing. When I first arrived, I was drinking a flat white with oat milk, because my local Maccas (the only drive thru open at 0350) is not very organised….usually they are unable to print me a receipt, and today they had no almond milk. Anyway, my coffee was good. I was shooting some bokeh light shots, and then doing some panning and just messing around until the sky was what I wanted it to be. As soon as I took this shot I knew it was ‘the one’ of many that I liked. Sometimes you have to get wet to get good photos! The worst thing that ever happened to me was I lost my iPhone to the ocean, like forever. Oh, and my dignity. It was very traumatic. Have you lost anything significant while taking photos at sunrise??

The SS Dicky was a steamer ship, wrecked on the Sunshine Coast during a cyclone in 1893. Sadly, most of the ribs and photographically fantastic parts of the wreck were removed by local council in 2015 and now, during low tide, this is what remains. One morning I went down to the beach and the sky was moody and dark, until the sun came up and then a little squinchy strip of colour appeared in the sky. I thought it suited a long exposure. Do you remember this shipwreck back in the days when more was visible? 🚢

I’ve been seeing a fair few ‘images’ created by AI lately on my socials, that’s Artificial Intelligence for those who haven’t heard of it……and okay, on one hand it’s pretty cool technology and all that, to be able to put in key words like 'tree' and 'beach' and 'reflection' and get a combo that looks amazing…..but on the other hand, I liken it to plastic surgery. It’s kind of…..fake…..and people are sadly not as accepting of reality anymore because they are getting used to fake. Like why are ladies (or men for that matter) in their 20s getting plastic surgery and fillers and b**b jobs?? They end up looking plastic, in my opinion (and I know some will not agree with this, but this is my page so whatevs). I feel for celebrities, especially women, as they get hounded if they are natural looking as they age (OMG wrinkles, no way), yet they also get hounded if they overdo plastic surgery, which, clearly, once you start, you have to keep going with it. I think it’s all a little gross that people are all starting to look alike. Anyway, back to images and art…..yes, I have appreciation for the talent of digital artists and AI-created work, but I also want people to be transparent in their work, like SAY it if it’s not real. It makes a mockery of those artists and photographers who actually put the work in, IRL instead of sitting on a computer. And yes, that’s a talent too, don’t get me wrong. Just don’t pretend it’s real, because it’s not. What do you think??

Tasmania has the most incredible temperate rainforest: pristine and fertile, like a dark green velvet jungle of amazingness. It’s so ALIVE! On my last trip when I was researching West Coast and Cradle Mountain, I was lost in those darn forests everywhere, so green, so lush, I can’t even describe them well. The challenge for me was to improve my own photography in the forest, because I’ve never been quite happy with it in the past. I tried to ditch my tripod but honestly, it’s so much better having one. Even in the daytime it’s so DARK in those forests….I tried using a polarising filter but didn’t like it. And also I used a less wide angle lens a lot, which I found was better to corral some of the vegetation and intense beauty into one composition. There’s so much of it!! I’d love to share it all with you in November, I’ve got 2 Tassie photo tours, one is East Coast including Bay of Fires, the other is West Coast including Cradle Mountain. As much as I enjoy landscapes (because nature just does what it does, no direction required), there are other things to photograph, and other times than just sunrise and sunset. On my Tassie photo tours I love to introduce people to things they may not have considered photographing before. I have developed a relationship with @melshell_oysters who allow us unimpeded access ‘behind the scenes’ of their very successful working oyster farm. I had kind of a breakthrough moment the other morning as I was taking photos. I thought, how do I explain to people the best way to improve your photography? And it made me think of THE GYM of all places. You may or may not know that I’ve successfully avoided gyms for most of my life, while still being active outdoors with walking, shuffle-jogging, paddling, surfing, kayaking, hula hooping, inline skating, downhill skiing, latin dancing and many other things. Oh, and I did crossfit many years ago for a very long time. But last year I decided to join a gym to assist in rehab after my knee surgery, and it’s been a really interesting year to say the least. Learning gym has been really hard (but thank you, TikTok weight lifting and mobility expert people, you are awesome, mwah ) but one thing has really stood out to me, and that is CONSISTENCY. Honestly, you really just have to show up consistently, and you will end up doing things at the gym. It’s kind of the same with photography. Just show up! Show up at sunrise, or sunset or whenever. Take your camera. Make a concerted effort to practice. Because guess what, all the training, tuition, and workshops in the world are not going to make you better. They only give you the TOOLS to get better. You still have to show up!! The more you do things, the better you get. Think of when you learned to drive a car. Think of learning another language. It’s all the same. Show up and your brain will start to remember. And I promise you will get results. 🧡

.
And hey, come to Tassie with me for HEAPS of practice. I’m an accredited tour operator with TITC (Tourism Industry Council Tasmania), I’m licensed with Parks Tasmania to conduct tours within parks and reserves, and I’m even a volunteer Tassie Tourism Ambassador, THAT’S how much I’m committed to sharing Tasmania with the world. The Edge of the World is wild and rugged and it’s one of the most western points in Tasmania. Now I bet when you first looked at this image, you saw BONES in the foreground, right? Well I did anyway. (what does that say about me?). Actually, it’s got soooo much driftwood: silvery grey, weathered, gorgeous driftwood, as far as the eye can see, stacked up and piled up. I loved the cross-cross water flow and the unpredictability of the surf. There’s a very cute plaque here too, with an inscription by local Brian Inder, it says: 
.
“I cast my pebble onto the shore of Eternity.
To be washed by the Ocean of time. It has shape, form, and substance.
It is me.
One day I will be no more. But my pebble will remain here.
On the shore of eternity.
Mute witness from the aeons.
That today I came and stood 
At the edge of the world.”
.
Since it’s so remote here, it’s not overrun by tourists, so it’s the perfect place to spend an afternoon, just enjoying the wild – and coincidentally…….one of the locations we visit on my newly created Tasmania West Coast + Cradle Mountain photo tour.  Why don’t you come along? ⭐
.

I have worked many, many varieties of jobs in my life. I’ve never chased ‘a career’ or the money, I lived and travelled in an old Kombi van for a while when hashtag vanlife was just part of life, not an Instagram thing. But one job really sticks in my mind: I was a snorkelling instructor on the Great Barrier Reef, working for an organisation that brought over American schoolkids from the middle of the country, without means to see the ocean or travel. Maybe it was a charity of some sort, I don’t recall. But I do remember that for a lot of those kids, it was the FIRST TIME they had ever seen the ocean!!! And I will never forget the impact that being in the ocean and seeing the underwater marine life had on these kids….they were just amazed and in awe of the ocean. It was so satisfying, teaching them to breathe calmly, and point out magical creatures underwater and explain relationships between fish. They had the time of their life. And I will never forget it. The ocean is so powerful and amazing, isn’t it. I lived in Alice Springs for a while and all I could think about was how far from the ocean I was. And now that I've been calling the Sunshine Coast home for over 20 years.....I don't think I ever want to leave. 💙

I think we can all agree that seascapes are probably my ‘lane’ of photography. That doesn’t mean I’m an expert by any means, nor am I a specialist in flow, or long exposures, it’s just what I tend to do the MOST of because I live so close to the beach and I love love love being at the beach at dawn with no-one else around, and I practice that style of photography the most. It’s also what I seem to teach the most, but I don’t limit myself. 

I also love travel and people of differing cultures, so I like to photograph them in their own environment (documentary/portraits I guess you could say). I appreciate architecture: lines and curves. And city lights. And textures. And food. And wildlife. So on my photo tours I like to add little snippets of OTHER, or non-landscape photography, because beauty is all around us. What you can count on is my patience, my professionalism and my dedication to helping you take better photos and share something new with you. Why don’t you explore the world with me? The old one was pulled down, and the jetty leading to it fell apart, and it was all taped off for ages and then finally….something happened. I didn’t want to disrespect the owner and walk onto the jetty but I thought it was ok to stand next to it and place my camera down on the timber boards, I like the low perspective because it’s tough to get a different shot of the same thing I’ve been photographing for…..years! Man, I love timber. I can’t wait until it weathers a bit more.

Questions about photographing flow……..well honestly. Sooo many questions I get about this topic. And it’s not that easy to answer because…..what shutter speed you want really depends on a)what you are trying to achieve (long misty exposures? Short flow?) and b)how fast is the water flowing and c)where do you want to place the water in your composition, d)how much light is on offer, and I could go on and on. For me….I try to choose a ‘main’ subject, like this big rock. And then I watch, and I watch some more (and this is why I like to bring coffee with me). I’m looking for the white foamy flow filling all the cracks and crevices and making nice designs. I usually don’t want water covering the rocks, but around the rocks, if that makes sense. If you come and do a private workshop with me, I’ve got @nisifiltersaustralia filter kits and filters you can use and I can share with you so much more about this beautiful way of photographing seascapes.

I get asked about what my footwear is when I’m out for beach sunrises, and the answer is….mostly I’m barefoot (there is nothing quite like feeling the flow of the ocean on my skin). If I’m going to a beach I know well, I prefer to have bare feet as they really ‘feel’ the rock surfaces and I feel are safer than wearing ‘rock shoes’ or ‘wet shoes’ which give me a false sense of security (and are not as grippy as they should be at times). It’s usually quite dark when I arrive as well, so I’m taking little mini steps and going slow. This changed when I was in Oregon a few months back, I was unfamiliar with the coastline and the beaches in general, so I felt it was safer to keep my hiking boots on. Occasionally I will wear rubber boots to certain beaches, especially if there is a thin layer of water – this (I believe) keeps me safer from getting stung by rockfish or stingrays. Basically I plan ahead – if it’s a new beach, you can be pretty sure that I’ve already checked it out the day before, in daylight. And the boot of my car is filled with shoe variations, thongs, wet shoes, rubber boots, towels and a million other things. What do you wear on your feet?

I feel that one of the challenges while learning to photograph flow is deciding how you want the water to look….smooth and milky? Swooshy lines? More movement or less? I actually liked the way this one turned out, showcasing water movement but also calmness……there’s nothing quite like standing thigh deep in the flow with your feet sinking and trying to keep your balance, while at the same time holding on to your tripod and making sure you don’t get knocked over. Oh, and try to find a subject that does not move, like this shipwreck. It’s massive and even though it is slowly being devoured by sand….it’s still there! And I may say, how good does it look in the golden light too. Lots of people come along on my workshops and tours and I spend a lot of time teaching how to use filters. It's not something you learn quickly, but practice will help you.

Girraween National Park…….WOW!! If you live in Queensland and haven’t been here, this is the perfect time of year to go with cooler weather and beautiful skies…. Girraween means ‘place of flowers’ and yes there’s plenty of those, and wallabies, and cool running water and granite outcrops and precariously balanced boulders covered with silvery grey and yellow lichen. Years ago I did a hike up to the giant balancing boulders but with all my physical and health limitations lately (translation: I am getting old), I was not up to it this time. I still managed to have a gorgeous stroll/walk in and around nature at its best (and saw plenty of hikers with tiny children and babies enjoying the walks too). Have you been? I even saw some red-winged parrots but I only had a wide angle lens on and so despite stalking them, the leaves were crunchy underfoot and I scared them off. Thanks to @nik_nik_nik50 for being a great model, as usual.

But…..try around 1 second to start with and see what you think. Let me know if that helps.

On the north Otago Coast on the South Island of New Zealand, magical things happen, and here are these gorgeous spherical boulders (lots and lots of them!) that weigh several tonnes and are up to two metres in height. Scientists have dated these boulders at around 65 million years!! According to Maori legend, the boulders are actually gourds washed ashore from the great voyaging canoe Araiteuru when it was wrecked upon landfall in New Zealand hundreds of years ago. You may not know this about me, but I generally don’t go out for astrophotography because I prefer to be home in my nice cozy bed (I’m way more a sunrise person) but occasionally an opportunity will present itself, so I went with @lifes.simple.things and @photographyby_kell out to where the dark skies are, the Somerset region in Queensland, where there is a gorgeous stick tree lake and I thought it would be a nice scene….and it was amazing! I had a great time.

I’m not even sure this happened, but the other day I was coming home mid-morning and there was a lady walking down the footpath, living her best life….in her white bathrobe. After our sunset session on my recent Hervey Bay workshop, I consulted my apps and saw that the Milky Way would be visible from our shooting location and the sky looked clear, so I invited my participants to join me (safety in numbers) to shoot the sky, and some of them did! The tide was slowly incoming out there on the sand flats, so it started to get a bit swampy, and we had to call it quits after a while. The backdrop: pitch black foreshore, occasional van headlights and the weird and creepy musical sound of an ice cream truck somewhere kept us company. I wonder if male photographers ever feel creeped out, or if it’s just women to have to be a million times more careful. Thanks for the company, ladies! ✨

Just making an observation here…..would love to know your thoughts. In all my years taking photos, I have chatted with so many people at sunrises and I find it really interesting that the people who offer unwarranted advice and opinionated critique ‘if you point your camera that way, it will look better’ and ‘why are you pointing your camera away from the sunrise? You’re missing the good stuff ‘ etc….ALL of those comments come from men. Usually older men. Not one single woman has ever offered her unasked-for opinion on what I’m doing. They just say, hey, and might ask a question like, ‘why are you dragging that old lounge along the beach?’ or ‘may I see what you’re taking a photo of?’. And don’t even get me started on the men who find it necessary to call me ‘sweetheart’.….

One very early morning I wandered around Darling Harbour, trying to find a good vantage point of the new W Hotel / Ribbon/ IMAX building in Sydney and my gosh, it’s tricky!! There’s so many overpasses and busy roads and craziness and I wasn’t really up for a whole bunch of walking after a knee procedure a few days prior, plus Google maps isn’t really the most helpful. 

I walked up and down a lot of stairs and behind buildings and around construction fences….mind you in the darkness which was also a little bit creepy. I’m quite fascinated with this building: the reflections, the thousands of windows and the distinctive curved shape. (thanks to the random lady I accosted in my wanderings who helped find me a staircase….she was awesome). I’m pretty sure this cool hotel (and 99% of hotels in general haha) will be totally out of my budget range when it opens soon but…..I’ve always got the outside, right? For this shot, I handheld my camera for one second. I had no tripods or filters and it was getting quite light but I managed to get some traffic blur going past. I’ve got a lot more architecture photography on another Instagram account called @wandacraswellarchitecture if you’re into that kind of thing.....a visit to Sydney always challenges me to shoot non-landscapes!

Last time I was out in Biloela it was a CORELLA APOCALYPSE 😲, the birds were all over the piles of seed and farm stuff (not a farm girl, don’t ask for crop or seed details) and flying all over the place and it was total chaos. I made sure if I was looking up, I had my mouth firmly closed because you never know what’s going to happen………but the light was incredible and I found joy in the birds, even though the farmers hate them. They really do make a mess. Sooo many questions……do they only look alike to us? To each other, do they look different from one other? How do they know what family they belong to? Do they even care about that? Are they all related? What do they eat when the seeds are all gone? How do they even know about the seed being there? SO. MANY. QUESTIONS.
.

Looking at this natural rock that looks like crazy paving stones, it jogged my memory to hopscotch and then to games I played with my girlfriends when I was young (that’s how my brain works, hope you can follow) and I used to play the most awesome game called ELASTICS. I know, right? You basically collected elastic bands (the skinny kind) and tied them together to make a really long rope that encircled 2 people who held it up like 6 feet apart, and they raised it to different levels and you had to jump in and out and twirl as you did it. 

So the idea was to not touch the elastics but to jump over them, and the elastic controllers challenged the jumper by lifting it up and down randomly. Did anyone else play this??? OR AM I TOTALLY DELUDED!!? We also played on monkey bars (sitting up on top of it and then dropping backwards and swinging) and I’m amazed that I never smashed my head, but anyways.
.

If you had been watching my technique for getting this shot, it would have amused you to no end. Sometimes in these big crack crevices I try to rest one leg of my tripod all the way to the other side, to make the positioning more central. But the space was too big, and since I have the broken body of a 56-year old and not a flexi miracle body like a 20-year old, straddling the crevice was not going to work either. So I ditched the tripod altogether and hung my hand low with my camera (of course with no camera strap) into the deep divide and hoped for the best. What fun!

I was just perusing an online menu for a new restaurant, and was struck how pretentious and ridiculous some of the words used were. Descriptive words like ‘deconstructed’…..I just want a piece of chocolate cake, thank you. No need to deconstruct it in little piles on a huge plate with some crumbs thrown around for good measure, and a smear of what looks like to be mud on the plate. Yuck. And unless I’m in a French restaurant, there’s no need for phrases like ‘pommes puree’ (ummmm mashed potatoes) and so on. I’ve been here on the coast for over 20 years….never met more than one or two who speak or even understand the French language, so why try to confuse people….to seem more intelligent? Or cultured? What do you think? (don’t even get me started on HAND CUT FRIES ......
.

People often ask, when is the best time for landscape photography? And for me, it is in the golden hour, in the hour before sunrise, when the light is saturated and amazing and soft. Of course sometimes it’s not always possible (when I travel, I try to make the best out of whatever time I’m in a location and sometimes that’s in the middle of the day!). Queensland, Australia, where I live, is a special place, our sunrises in summer are well before 5am ( I KNOW!!! I am often asked, what are my most used filters in my kit? Now I own a heap of filters (and by the way I have extra ones you can try on my private and group workshops) and looking back at my posts over the last, say 6-12 months, I would say there’s 2 filters that make an appearance A LOT. And they are the @nisifiltersaustralia 3-stop Neutral Density filter and the Medium Graduated filter. My style of shooting is often shorter exposures like 1 second, often to capture flow, and the 3-stopND is perfect for this. It also allows me to play with other settings like ISO and aperture without having to change the filter out (handy when I’m straddling a rock crevice with waves swooshing in). The other filter I use, darkens the sky ever so slightly, and that brings the exposure closer to the foreground. (If you are a photographer and are baffled by all of this mumbo jumbo, I teach the use of filters a whole lot so book a sesh with me!).

Mooloolaba Beach on NY morning……I couldn’t park where I normally do because there was still clean-up going on from NYEve, I parked further down the road and then kept seeing drunken groups of people wandering aimlessly through the still-closed café areas on the street, and then on the actual beach my heart was warmed by seeing a bunch of random people with white bags collecting rubbish (was it a group> was it organised?). 

I collected a whole bunch of what looked like broken plastic test tube shaped things, maybe broken light sticks (but they seemed bigger than that), and fibro of different colours, and broken glass. I get so much out of collecting little bits of rubbish, I encourage you to do the same (if you’re not already). Imagine if everyone visiting the beach picked up a few things, how amazing! We are very lucky here in Australia to have fairly clean beaches anyway, but we need to be vigilant.
